---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/url";
---

<Layout title="About" pageType="about">
  <article class="content about prose">
    <h1 class="display">About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm a software engineer working in production data and LLM systems.
      Right now I'm at a Perth capital management firm, building the
      pipeline that ingests ASX market filings, runs structured extraction
      through the Anthropic Batch API, and feeds the analytics frontend
      the team uses for cross-company analysis.
    </p>

    <p>
      I came at this sideways. I did a BA in philosophy at Murdoch in
      2013. Reading carefully, not jumping to conclusions, and being
      patient with ambiguity turned out to be useful for engineering,
      though it took me a while to notice.
    </p>

    <p>
      From 2018 to 2022 I edited research papers at MDPI, an academic
      publisher. About two thousand manuscripts across biology, chemistry,
      materials science, and a long tail of others. Most of the job was
      clarity work: figuring out what an author actually meant when the
      sentence on the page said something slightly different. That turns
      out to be a lot like prompt engineering, and a lot like designing
      schemas that don't break when real data shows up.
    </p>

    <p>
      I'd done a Cert IV in object-oriented programming at TAFE earlier
      and kept coding on the side. In 2025 I finished a Postgraduate
      Diploma in IT (Software Engineering) at UNE, GPA 6.88. It taught me
      the things you usually only get from formal CS: how systems are
      designed, where they break, what's worth abstracting.
    </p>

    <p>
      The current work pulls all of that together. The pipeline runs every
      day, classifies the new filings, pulls text out of PDFs, and submits
      batches to Claude for structured extraction (cheaper than real-time
      inference, by a fair margin). A point-in-time database handles the
      messy parts of historical market data: ticker changes, delistings,
      sector reclassifications. A Next.js frontend on top lets the team
      look at companies side-by-side or drill into any single history. Day
      to day that's Python, TypeScript, Postgres, Anthropic batch jobs,
      and whatever deployment plumbing the week needs.
    </p>

    <h2>What I work with</h2>

    <p>
      Currently working with Python, TypeScript, Next.js (App Router + React
      Server Components), Supabase, Postgres, and the Anthropic Batch API.
      Comfortable with React, Astro, MERN-stack apps, OAuth via Next-Auth,
      Flask, and self-hosted infrastructure on Proxmox.
    </p>

    <h2>How I work</h2>

    <p>
      A lot of what I do is critical asking: working out what to ask of
      the data, the codebase, the LLM, or whoever wrote the requirements,
      instead of jumping straight to what to write. With LLMs in the loop
      the bottleneck has shifted from writing to asking. I write about
      that on the <a href={withBase("/writing")}>writing page</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about {
    padding: var(--space-2xl) 0;
  }
  .display {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-l);
    max-width: var(--content-width);
  }
  .prose h2 {
    margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-m);
  }
</style>
